## Setup

Camera was connected to a USB power measurement dongle that was connected to the Mac computer and the power supply. The USB dongle measures the current used by the USB connection and the power supply measures the current drawn by the camera.

![][image1]

![][image2]  
First tests were performed with vendor software:  
![][image3]

## Test 1: Sequential images without cooling

Ran a script for 3000 exposures of 0.01s each (2s delay in between exposures) with cooling disabled.  
This test was performed using the camera software for MAC.  
Result: Power supply oscillates between 0.14A and 0.17A. USB power monitor stays at 0.017A. Camera temperature: 29.3ºC  
![][image4]  
![][image5]![][image6]

## Test 1: Sequential images with cooling enabled

Ran a script for 3000 exposures of 0.01s each (2s delay in between exposures) with cooling enabled with setpoint \-40ºC.  
This test was performed using the camera software for MAC.  
Results: Once cooling was enabled, camera started to ramp-up cooling power. Measured currents were around the following numbers:  
13% \- 0.22A  
25% \- 0.30A  
50% \- 0.60A  
60% \- 0.80A  
70% \- 1.00A  
80% \- 1.25A  
90% \- 1.57A  
100% \- 1.85A  
No changes were detected on the USB power monitoring. Camera temperature went down to \-14ºC until the test was stopped.  
![][image7]  
![][image8]

## Test 3: Further testing

- With the camera cooling in the state left by the last test, I experimented changing the gain, binning and other parameters and no change in the power consumption was detected.  
- I also tested removing the USB power monitor (to be sure that the interface was USB3.0 and not downgraded to USB2.0) and measured again the power consumption with the least exposure time and the cooling at 100%, and still the power consumption stayed below 2.0A.  
- Tested with ASICap software, which is intended to be a faster video capture mode with minimum exposure time (32µs) and cooler on, and had similar current consumption for 270M/s rate.
